{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603291"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:35:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:35:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15734"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15734"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0,0.38,0.04,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8425"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67273"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8425"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15734"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52725"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1258"},{"type":"tags","id":"1793"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7037"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20279"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22521"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67273"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with three months of increasing abdominal distension and early satiety. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Her abdomen is distended with shifting dullness. A CT scan reveals bilateral complex right ovarian mass with peritoneal deposits and ascites (Image). At surgery, the ovarian mass is removed along with omental deposits. Microscopy shows complex papillary architecture with marked nuclear pleomorphism, frequent mitoses, and scattered psammoma bodies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely histological diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clear cell carcinoma","Mucinous, benign","Mucinous carcinoma","Serous, benign","Serous carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and histological features are typical of ovarian high-grade serous carcinoma. This is the most common type of ovarian cancer, accounting for about 70% of cases. The presence of complex papillary architecture, marked nuclear atypia, frequent mitoses, and psammoma bodies are characteristic features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerous carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in postmenopausal women with advanced stage disease, often with peritoneal spread at diagnosis. The bilateral involvement seen here is also typical of serous carcinoma, which frequently arises from the fallopian tubes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerous benign\u003C/strong\u003E tumours (cystadenomas) show simple papillary architecture with uniform nuclei and no significant atypia or mitotic activity. They are typically unilateral and confined to the ovary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMucinous benign\u003C/strong\u003E tumours are characterized by tall columnar mucin-producing cells with minimal stratification and bland nuclei. They lack the complex papillary architecture seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMucinous carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows intestinal-type differentiation with abundant intracellular mucin. Unlike serous carcinoma, mucinous carcinomas are usually unilateral and confined to the ovary at presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClear cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows clear or hobnail cells arranged in tubulocystic, papillary, or solid patterns. The cells have clear cytoplasm due to glycogen content, which is not seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional immunohistochemical staining would typically show diffuse p53 positivity (indicating TP53 mutation) and high Ki-67 proliferation index in high-grade serous carcinoma, helping to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Serous carcinoma is the most common type of ovarian cancer, typically presenting as a complex cystic mass with papillary projections.","Key histological features of serous carcinoma include complex papillary architecture, marked nuclear atypia, and psammoma bodies.","Immunohistochemistry showing p53 mutation and high Ki-67 index helps distinguish high-grade serous carcinoma from other ovarian tumours."],"references":["Hatano Y, Hatano K, Tamada M, Morishige KI, Tomita H, Yanai H, Hara A. A Comprehensive Review of Ovarian Serous Carcinoma. Adv Anat Pathol. 2019 Sep;26(5):329-339. doi: 10.1097/PAP.0000000000000243. PMID: 31368906; PMCID: PMC7043727.","Momenimovahed Z, Tiznobaik A, Taheri S, Salehiniya H. Ovarian cancer in the world: epidemiology and risk factors. Int J Womens Health. 2019 Apr 30;11:287-299. doi: 10.2147/IJWH.S197604. PMID: 31118829; PMCID: PMC6500433","Cho KR, Shih IeM. Ovarian cancer. Annu Rev Pathol. 2009;4:287-313. doi: 10.1146/annurev.pathol.4.110807.092246. PMID: 18842102; PMCID: PMC2679364","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52725"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15734"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21285"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21285"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/DZwzwoWVrTerSBj0jkZTKABksgnd0n.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/DZwzwoWVrTerSBj0jkZTKABksgnd0n.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":476,"height":636}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52725"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T12:18:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T12:19:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8425"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67273"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group"